Things to Keep in Mind While Creating and Importing Modules in Python

A module is simply a Python file (.py) that contains functions, variables, classes, or code that can be reused in other programs.

While Creating a Module
| Point                      | Explanation                                                                                                         |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Use Meaningful Names       | Give the module a clear and descriptive name such as `calculator.py`, `database.py`, or `student.py`.               |
| Follow Naming Rules        | Module names should be valid Python identifiers. Use lowercase letters and underscores.                             |
| Avoid Spaces               | Never use spaces in module names. Use `student_data.py` instead of `student data.py`.                               |
| Avoid Python Keywords      | Don't use names like `class.py`, `for.py`, `if.py`, etc.                                                            |
| Avoid Built-in Names       | Don't name modules `math.py`, `random.py`, `os.py`, etc., because they may conflict with Python's built-in modules. |
| Keep Related Code Together | Functions and classes in a module should be related to the same purpose.                                            |
| Add Documentation          | Include comments or docstrings explaining the module's purpose.                                                     |
| Write Reusable Code        | Avoid writing code that runs immediately when the module is imported.                                               |
| Use Functions and Classes  | Organize code into functions and classes instead of writing everything at the top level.                            |
| Test the Module            | Verify that all functions work correctly before importing them elsewhere.                                           |


Use if __name__ == "__main__" for Testing
When creating a module, testing code should be placed inside:

if __name__ == "__main__":
    # test code

Why?
This ensures the test code runs only when the module is executed directly and not when it is imported.

While Importing a Module
| Point                     | Explanation                                                                          |
| ------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| Module Must Exist         | The module file must be available in the current directory or Python path.           |
| Correct Spelling          | Use the exact module name while importing.                                           |
| No `.py` Extension        | Import using the module name only, not `module.py`.                                  |
| Avoid Circular Imports    | Module A should not unnecessarily import Module B if Module B imports Module A.      |
| Import Only What You Need | Import specific functions when possible to improve readability.                      |
| Use Aliases Carefully     | Aliases can shorten long module names but should remain meaningful.                  |
| Avoid Wildcard Imports    | `from module import *` can create confusion and naming conflicts.                    |
| Check Dependencies        | Ensure imported modules are installed if they are external libraries.                |
| Keep Imports Organized    | Usually place all imports at the beginning of the file.                              |
| Understand Scope          | Imported names become available only in the current file unless explicitly exported. |

Common Import Styles
| Import Style               | Example                                  | Use Case                                   |
| -------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ |
| Import Entire Module       | `import calculator`                      | When many functions are needed             |
| Import Specific Function   | `from calculator import add`             | When only a few functions are needed       |
| Import Multiple Functions  | `from calculator import add, sub`        | When several specific functions are needed |
| Import with Alias          | `import calculator as calc`              | Shorter names                              |
| Import Function with Alias | `from calculator import add as addition` | Avoid name conflicts                       |

Common Mistakes
| Mistake                             | Problem                               |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| Naming module `math.py`             | Conflicts with built-in `math` module |
| Using spaces in file names          | Import errors                         |
| Forgetting file location            | Python cannot find the module         |
| Using `from module import *`        | Namespace pollution                   |
| Circular imports                    | Runtime errors and maintenance issues |
| Running unwanted code during import | Unexpected behavior                   |

Module Design Best Practices
✅ Good Module
calculator.py
├── add()
├── subtract()
├── multiply()
├── divide()
└── test code inside __main__

❌ Poor Module
calculator.py
├── add()
├── student_details()
├── database_connection()
├── game_logic()
└── unrelated code mixed together

A module should focus on one responsibility.

One-Line Definition

A good Python module should be well-named, focused on a single purpose, reusable, and easy to import without causing conflicts or unwanted side effects.
